Lateralization

The first trait I tested was lateralization. This trait was broken into directionally-dependent lateralization as well as absolute lateralization. The first thing I did was visualize both traits and graphed them on half-eye violin plots that were then combined.

lat <- ggplot(Lat, aes(x = Treatment, y = Lat.Index, fill = Treatment)) + stat_halfeye( .width = c(0.66, 0.89, 0.95, 0.99),  slab_alpha = 0.6,  point_interval = "mean_qi", position = position_dodge(width = 1)) + labs(x = "Treatment", y = "Lateralization") +  theme_classic() + facet_wrap(Lat$Temperature) + scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(-100, 100, by = 25)) + 
  scale_x_discrete(limits = level_order)  + scale_fill_manual(values = c('dodgerblue', 'orange', 'red'),

abslat <- ggplot(Lat, aes(x = Treatment, y = Abs.Lat.Index, fill = Treatment)) + stat_halfeye( .width = c(0.66, 0.89, 0.95, 0.99),  slab_alpha = 0.6,  point_interval = "mean_qi", position = position_dodge(width = 1), adjust = 3 ) + labs(x = "Treatment", y = "Absolute Lateralization") + theme_classic() + facet_wrap(Lat$Temperature) +

Directional-dependent lateralization

We tested this trait with multiple different glms and glmers. We found that Parent pair was singular and did not contribute to random effects. The gmler_latt with tank as a random effect was most fit.

y <- cbind(Lat$L, Lat$R)

glm_Lat <- glm(y~ Treatment * Temperature , family = "binomial", data = Lat)

glmer_Lat <- glmer(y~ Treatment * Temperature + (1|Tank..) , family = "binomial", data = Lat) 

glmer_Lat2 <- glmer(y~ Treatment * Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair/Tank..), family = "binomial", data = Lat) 
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')
glmer_latt <- glmer(y~ Treatment + Temperature + (1|Tank..), family = "binomial", data = Lat) 


AIC(glm_Lat, glmer_Lat, glmer_Lat2, glmer_latt)
##            df      AIC
## glm_Lat     6 1155.965
## glmer_Lat   7 1151.407
## glmer_Lat2  8 1153.407
## glmer_latt  5 1148.995

We tested with other family models but they were all similar so we kept the binomial model.

glmer_Lat <- glmer(y~ Treatment * Temperature + (1|Tank..) , family = "binomial", data = Lat) 
glmer_Lat3 <- glmer(y~ Treatment * Temperature + (1|Tank..) , family = binomial(link="probit"), data = Lat) 
glmer_Lat4 <- glmer(y~ Treatment * Temperature + (1|Tank..) ,family = binomial(link="cloglog"), data = Lat)

Absolute lateralization

We used cumulative linked mixed models to model ordinal data such as the lateralization index.

Lat$Abs.Lat.Index <- factor(Lat$Abs.Lat.Index, 
                       levels = c(0, 20, 40, 60, 80, 100),
                       ordered = TRUE) #changing Abs.Lat.Index score to factor #changing Abs.Lat.Index score to factor

Model_abslat <- clmm(Abs.Lat.Index ~ Treatment * Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair) + (1|Tank..), data = Lat)

Interaction showed no effect.

abslat_1 <- clmm(Abs.Lat.Index ~ Treatment:Temperature + Treatment + Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair) + (1|Tank..), data = Lat)

Boldness Score

The boldness score was turned into an ordinal factor and then models were run.

Lat$Boldness <- factor(Lat$Boldness, 
                       levels = 1:7, 
                       labels = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7),
                       ordered = TRUE) #changing Boldness score to factor

Model_bold <- clmm(Boldness ~ Treatment * Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair) + (1|Tank..), data = Lat)

Here, we ran an anova between two cumulative linked mixed models to check if the two fixed factors had an interaction.

bold1 <- clmm(Boldness ~ Treatment:Temperature + Treatment + Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair) + (1|Tank..), data = Lat)
bold2 <- clmm(Boldness ~ Treatment + Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair) + (1|Tank..), data = Lat)
anova(bold1,bold2)
## Likelihood ratio tests of cumulative link models:
##  
##       formula:                                                                                     
## bold2 Boldness ~ Treatment + Temperature + (1 | Parent.Pair) + (1 | Tank..)                        
## bold1 Boldness ~ Treatment:Temperature + Treatment + Temperature + (1 | Parent.Pair) + (1 | Tank..)
##       link: threshold:
## bold2 logit flexible  
## bold1 logit flexible  
## 
##       no.par    AIC  logLik LR.stat df Pr(>Chisq)
## bold2     11 560.00 -269.00                      
## bold1     13 563.63 -268.81  0.3734  2     0.8297

There was no interaction so we tested the fixed factors individually. Each model was compared using AIC to determine the best fit.

bold3 <- clmm(Boldness ~ Treatment + Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair) , data = Lat)
bold4 <- clmm(Boldness ~ Treatment + Temperature + (1|Tank..) , data = Lat)
bold5 <- clm(Boldness ~ Treatment + Temperature, data = Lat)
AIC(bold1, bold2, bold3, bold4, bold5)

## bold2 11 560.0014
## bold3 10 558.0936
## bold4 10 560.7411

Time to Emergence

We tested various models to look at Time of emergence. The Zi gamma distribition zig_TOE4 was best fit.

lm_ToE <- lm(Time.to.Emergence ~ Treatment * Temperature , data = Lat)
lmer_ToE <- lmer(Time.to.Emergence ~Treatment * Temperature + (1|Tank..), data = Lat)
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')
lmer_ToE2 = lmer(Time.to.Emergence ~ Treatment * Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair), data = Lat)
## boundary (singular) fit: see help('isSingular')
zig_ToE3 <- glmmTMB(Time.to.Emergence ~Treatment * Temperature ,  ziformula = ~1, family = ziGamma(link = "log"), data = Lat)
zig_ToE4 <- glmmTMB(Time.to.Emergence ~Treatment + Temperature ,  ziformula = ~1, family = ziGamma(link = "log"), data = Lat)
zig_ToE <- glmmTMB(Time.to.Emergence ~Treatment * Temperature + (1|Tank..),  ziformula = ~1, family = ziGamma(link = "log"), data = Lat)
zig_ToE2 <- glmmTMB(Time.to.Emergence ~Treatment * Temperature + (1|Parent.Pair/Tank..),  ziformula = ~1, family = ziGamma(link = "log"), data = Lat)

AIC(lm_ToE, lmer_ToE, lmer_ToE2, zig_ToE, zig_ToE2, zig_ToE3, zig_ToE4)
##           df      AIC
## lm_ToE     7 640.1817
## lmer_ToE   8 620.6898
## lmer_ToE2  8 620.6898
## zig_ToE    9 615.3111
## zig_ToE2  10 617.3111
## zig_ToE3   8 613.3111
## zig_ToE4   6 609.9667
